Exploratory Data Analysis of Metro Bike Dataset

 This is a dataset of shared bike trips from the Los Angeles Metro Bike Share, which is distributed under a ODbL license. The main purposes of this work are to pre-processing the data, to find some potential patterns of user habits and predict the trends of the trips.

Overview of the Data

The data contains 15 columns and each row of data recorded the main information of a trip.

Column Description Datatype
trip_id Locally unique integer that identifies the trip Interval
duration Length of trip in minutes Ratio
start_time The begin date/time of the trip Ratio
end_time The end date/time of the trip Ratio
start_station The station ID where the trip originated Interval
start_lat The latitude of the start station Interval
start_lon The longitude of the start station Interval
end_station The station ID where the trip terminated Interval
end_lat The latitude of the end station Interval
end_lon The longitude of the end station Interval
bike_id Locally unique integer that identifies the bike Interval
plan_duration The number of days of the passholder's ride plan Ratio
trip_route_category Round Trip or One Way Nominal
passholder_type The name of the passholder's plan Ordinal
bike_type the kind of bike: standard padal/electric/smart Nominal

Data Cleaning and Data Transformation

Identifying and Dropping Irrelevant Data

Column trip_id is the id of a trip and not meaningful for further analysis. Additionally, end_time is meaningful, but it can be calculated by start_time + duration, which means it is redundant. Besides, column trip_route_category is the type of trip such as round trip or one way, which means start_station == end_station and it is also redundant.

Mapping the stations to locations

In[15]:
# A station map to store the latitudes and longitudes of each station
def calculate_station_map():
    _station_map = {}
    for _stations in (trips[['start_station', 'start_lat', 'start_lon']].drop_duplicates(),
                    trips[['end_station', 'end_lat', 'end_lon']].drop_duplicates()):
        for i in range(len(_stations)):
            _row = _stations.iloc[i]
            _station_map.setdefault(int(_row.iloc[0]), [_row.iloc[1], _row.iloc[2]])
    return _station_map

# Calculating the station map
station_map = calculate_station_map()
for _station in ms_stations:
    station_map.pop(_station)

The nearest stations and the predicting positions for missed-location stations

In[16]:
for ms_station in ms_stations:
    # find the nearest 2 stations of each missing-value station
    nearest = trips[(trips.start_station == ms_station)
        & (trips.end_station != ms_station)
        & (trips.duration == 1) 
        & (- pd.isnull(trips.end_lat))] \
        .end_station.value_counts()[:2]
    # calculate latitude and longitude by loations of nearlest staions
    lat, lon = np.round(np.mean(np.array([station_map[n] for n in nearest.index]),axis=0), 6)
    # update latitude and longitude values to trips table
    trips.start_lat = np.where(trips.start_station == ms_station, lat, trips.start_lat)
    trips.start_lon = np.where(trips.start_station == ms_station, lon, trips.start_lon)
    trips.end_lat = np.where(trips.end_station == ms_station, lat, trips.end_lat)
    trips.end_lon = np.where(trips.end_station == ms_station, lon, trips.end_lon)
    # update latitude and longitude values to station map
    station_map.setdefault(ms_station, np.array([lat, lon]))
    print('the location of station {} is ({},{})'.format(ms_station, lat, lon))

Identifying and handling outliers

In[17]:
# A function to show outliers for numeric columns
def boxplot_numeric_columns():
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=3,figsize=(12, 4))
    plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=.5)
    trips.boxplot(column='duration', ax=axes[0,0])
    trips.boxplot(column='plan_duration', ax=axes[1,0])
    trips.boxplot(column='start_lat', ax=axes[0,1])
    trips.boxplot(column='start_lon', ax=axes[0,2])
    trips.boxplot(column='end_lat', ax=axes[1,1])
    trips.boxplot(column='end_lon', ax=axes[1,2])

# box plot
boxplot_numeric_columns()

Handling Outliers for Durations

# Calculate Inter Quartile Range
q1 = trips.duration.quantile(0.25)
q3 = trips.duration.quantile(0.75)

# calculate upper limit
upper_limit = q3 + 1.5 * (q3 - q1)
print(f'Q1: {q1}, Q3: {13}, upper limit: {upper_limit}')

Q1: 6.0, Q3: 13, upper limit: 46.0
Over 95% trips were <= 76.0 minutes and over 98% trips were <= 184.0 minutes.

The result shown that the suggested upper limit is 46 minutes and riding time recommonded by service companies was less than 60 minutes [2]. Thus durations within [60, 180] are replaced by 60 and rows with durations over 180 are removed.

In[19]:
# removing outliers
pre_length = len(trips)
trips = trips[trips.duration < 180]
trips.duration = np.where(trips.duration > 60, 60, trips.duration)
print(f'{pre_length - len(trips)} rows were removed.')

1887 rows were removed.

# A map view of stations
def map_view_stations():
    locations = []
    for k, (lat, lon) in station_map.items():
        locations.append([k, lat, lon])
    location_df = pd.DataFrame(locations, columns=['station', 'lat', 'lon'])
    location_df[['lat', 'lon']].plot.scatter(x='lat', y='lon', figsize=(12, 8))
    for i in range(len(location_df)):
        row = location_df.iloc[i]
        plt.text(row.lat + 0.005, row.lon, str(int(row.station)), size=8)

Transformation of Categorical Data

Transformation of Datetime

Generally speaking, bike users choose relatively fixed dates and times to travel. For this reason, start_time should be replaced by day of year, day of week and hour, so that the rules are easier to be found.

In[26]:
# extract dates and hours for further analysis and visualization
trips['day_of_year'] = trips.start_time.dt.day_of_year
trips['day_of_week'] = trips.start_time.dt.day_of_week
trips['hour'] = trips.start_time.dt.hour
trips['date'] = trips.start_time.dt.date

Extracting Data for Training Dataset

The encoded dataset will completely change the data, including values and data types. Thus it is helpful to store data into a new variable.

In[27]:
# define a dataframe for the output dataset
trips_final = trips[['duration', 'start_lat', 'start_lon', 'end_lat', 'end_lon',
                     'plan_duration', 'passholder_type', 'bike_type',
                     'day_of_year', 'day_of_week', 'hour']]

Transformation of Categorical Data - Encoding

There are two categorical columns, passholder_type and bike_type, to be encoded. As they seem more like ordianal, ordinal encoding is applied for these columns.

In[28]:
# define mappings
passholder_type_mapping = {'Walk-up': 0, 'One Day Pass': 1, 'Monthly Pass': 2, 'Flex Pass': 3,'Annual Pass': 4, 'Testing': 5}
bike_type_mapping = {'standard': 0, 'electric': 1, 'smart': 2}

# convert columns to categorical datatype
trips_final = trips_final.astype({'passholder_type': 'category','bike_type': 'category'})

# convert columns to number
trips_final = trips_final.assign(passholder_type=lambda _r: _r.passholder_type.cat.rename_categories(passholder_type_mapping),
                                 bike_type=lambda _r: _r.bike_type.cat.rename_categories(bike_type_mapping))

plt.xticks(rotation=90);

The above graph shows that electric and standard pedal-powered bikes have obvious periodic changes by weeks. Additionally, after 1st of September, there was an increase on standard bikes. Conversely, there was a slightly decrease on electric bikes.

The Difference of the Trip Numbers between Entering and Leaving Trips of a Station

Due to the particularity of the business, users are not responsible for balancing the supply of bikes. Some anomalies found in the data are helpful to improve the quality of service.

In[34]:
# numbers of trips of start stations
start_station_nums = trips.start_station.value_counts()
# numbers of trips of end stations
end_station_nums = trips.end_station.value_counts()
difference = []
for station, in_num in end_station_nums.items():
    out_num = start_station_nums.get(station, 0)
    difference.append([station, in_num - out_num])
difference.sort(key=lambda x: -x[1])
difference = pd.DataFrame(difference, columns=['station', 'num'])
difference = difference.set_index('station')
difference.iloc[[0,1,-2,-1]]

A Map View of the Difference of the Trip Numbers between Entering and Leaving a Station

As the result shown above, there were more bikes drived-in than drived-out to some stations. It is significant to show the problem on a map.

In[35]:
# Wraping a list for station information
stations = [[station, *station_map[station], difference.loc[station].num, start_station_nums.loc[station]]
               for station in trips.start_station.unique()]
stations_df = pd.DataFrame(stations, columns=['station', 'lat', 'lon', 'sur', 'trip_num'])

locations_diff = stations_df[stations_df.sur >= 0]
ax = locations_diff[['lat', 'lon']].plot.scatter(x='lat', y='lon', c='r', s=locations_diff.sur/5, figsize=(12,8), label='in > out')
stations_less = stations_df[stations_df.sur < 0]
stations_less[['lat', 'lon']].plot.scatter(ax=ax, x='lat', y='lon', c='g', s=abs(stations_less.sur)/5, label='in < out')
# the list of top difference of trips
top_differences = difference[:10].index.to_list() + difference[-10:].index.to_list()
# mark station ids and differences on the graph
for i in range(len(stations_df)):
    _row = stations_df.iloc[i]
    if _row.station in top_differences:
        plt.text(_row.lat, _row.lon, f'{int(_row.station)}({difference.loc[_row.station].num})', size=8)
plt.title(f'The Difference between Entering and Leaving Trips in Stations')
plt.xlabel('latitude')
plt.ylabel('longitude')
plt.legend(loc='upper right');

The above graph shows that the short-term effect of bikes occur at several nearby stations, resulting in more uneven distribution.

Summary

Overall, the dataset was well collected by sharing bike servicesy. Though there were some missing values of locations, it has little impact. The data exploratory analysis above shows that:

  • The stations were concentrated in several areas and were relocated closer during data processing.
  • The trips have periodic changes by weeks and by days.
  • The short-term effect of bikes occur at nearby stations, resulting in more uneven distribution.
  • There were some popular stations contributed lots of short or long trips.

Finally, selected columns were standarized and the dataset was saved to a file ('data/metro_final.csv') for further mordeling.
